\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Blank
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let A be a non-associative K-algebra where K is a field.
 Now equip A with a K-linear map λ:A->A, called the perturbation of A.
 I'm going to give you a few definitions now:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
1) We say A permutative if the the permutative law holds which says that
 for all a,b,c,d in A we have (λ(a)λ(b))λ(cd) = λ(ab)(λ(c)λ(d)).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
2) We say A is homassociative if the the homassociative law holds which
 says that for all a,b,c in A we have (ab)λ(c) = λ(a)(bc).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
3) We say A is multiplicative if the multiplicative law holds which says
 λ(ab)=λ(a)λ(b) for all a,b in A.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let me give you my interpretation of what is going on: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Suppose A is a permutative algebra.
 The idea is that when we multiply two elements in A together, we should
 simultaneously perturb all other elements as well.
 Thus a permutative algebra captures the idea of a system in which applying
 some multiplication operation to parts of that system will cause the entire
 system to be perturbed simultaneously.
 Can you think of any physical or mathematical systems which behave like
 this, for which permutative algebras could model? 
\end_layout

\end_body
